               <dateline><!--If there's no date line, remove this element. Record in the order in which it is written on the letter.-->
                  <placeName ref="Id_where"/>
                  <date when="1843-03-30">March 30, 1843</date></dateline>
               <salute>
                  <persName>
                     <!-- Use if letter has a saluation ("Dear Sir," for example). If not, delete this line.-->
                  </persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>Trim - March 30<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1843
               Your <hi rend="underline">lark</hi> sang delight<lb/>
               fully at its rising, and in<lb/>
               the whole of its flight &amp;<lb/>
               descent - How much<choice> 
                  <orig>plea<lb/>
                     sure</orig>
                  <reg>pleasure</reg>
               </choice>
               you gave dearest <choice>
                  <orig>mo-<lb/>
                     ther</orig>
                  <reg>mother</reg>
               </choice>
               ther you can hardly know<lb/>
               unless you could see &amp; hear<lb/>
               behind your back as well<lb/>
               as before your face -<lb/>
               I never was more delighted<lb/>
               than by the surprise of<lb/>
               seeing your dear rosy face<lb/>
               lightening upon me and so<lb/>
               affectionately &amp; unexpectedly<lb/>
               and I only wish I had that<lb/>
               hug over again -<lb/>
               
               We all, - meaning Harriet<lb/>
               &amp; myself<lb/></p>
               
               
            <p>have agreed that under<lb/>
               your staid, prove, every <lb/>
               day demeanour and <lb/>
               matronly <del>habits</del> and<lb/>
               Grandmotherian habits<lb/>
               you have a <hi rend="underline">deal</hi> of romance<lb/>
               deep down that sprouts up<lb/>
               to day unexpectedly every<lb/>
               now and then - Kind <choice>
                <orig>fa<lb/> 
                   ther</orig>
                  <reg>father</reg>
               </choice>
               ther for you - And God bless<lb/>
               you for it - and often may<lb/>
               it sprout for our delight<lb/>
               
               I hope dearest mother<lb/>
               that the pleasure you have<lb/>
               given &amp; received I trust<lb/>
               on this little occasion will<lb/>
               encourage you to indulge<lb/>
               yourself in future when<lb/></p>
               
               <p>ever opportunity &amp; <choice>
                    <orig>tempta-<lb/>
                       tion</orig>
                    <reg>temptation</reg>
               </choice>
                  well join for a <hi rend="underline">Spry</hi>
                  (an American word acknow<lb/>
                  (ledged by American dictionary<lb/>
                  (which Harriet rich in Dic<hi rend="superscript">s</hi>possesses
               I am so glad that<lb/>
                  you had the luck at<lb/>
                  the last moment to<lb/>
                  catch the unpacking<lb/>
                  of the picture of Walter<lb/>
                  though between you &amp;<lb/>
                  I it is but a sorry drawing<lb/>
                  and does not suit (in my<lb/>
                  opinion the place where it<lb/>
                  now is viz over the Bishop<lb/>
                  of Meaths admirable head<lb/>
                  and between you &amp; Francis<lb/>
                  I hope Mary Anne &amp; Charlotte<lb/>
                  will take it up to their own<lb/></p>
            
               <p>room - It does not match any<lb/>
                  thing in this room - &amp; I cant<lb/>
                  abide it - But it was very good<lb/>
                  of Aunt Henrietta to get it done<lb/>
                  and to send it to Mary Anne &amp; C<lb/>
               A new music has just <choice>
                  <orig>ar-<lb/>
                  rived </orig>
                  <reg>arrived</reg>
               </choice>
               &amp; the room is all ears<lb/>
                  And Lucy is judging - and<lb/>
                  I am no judge but very<lb/>
                  affectionately yours<lb/>
                  ME<lb/>
               
            </p>
            <p>
               <!--More body paragraphs as needed.--></p>
            <p>
               <!--More body paragraphs as needed.-->
               <!--Where there's a page break record it inside the relevant body paragraph like this, 
                  with the self-closing page-break element. n="2" indicates the START of the second page.-->
               <pb n="2" facs="image2.jpg"/>
            </p>
            <p><!--More body paragraphs as needed.--></p>
            <closer>
               <!--include linebreaks, if used. example: <closer> Yours<lb/> Very sincerely<lb/> -->
            </closer>
            <postscript>
               <p>I am so glad you have <lb/>
                  Conde - Do you see in<lb/>
                  todays paper the report that<lb/>
                  Lord Mahon is to go <choice>
                     <orig>Embassa<lb/>
                        dor</orig>
                     <reg>Embassador</reg>
                  </choice>
                  to Spain - I hope it is<lb/>
                  done - it would suit &amp;<lb/>
                  gratify him so much<lb/>
                  Thank you for mentioning<lb/>
                  Marys delight on her sealed<lb/>
                  packet - Love to all<lb/></p>
            </postscript>
